text: FUN FACT based on Ame's question at 2:55:35: I don't have the answer but i learned recently that earth's spinning also effects the way currents move from surface to deep sea. On the surface they're mainly effected by the spinning in a way that causes the clockwise/counter-clockwise movement of water in the north/south hemisphere (ex: the direction water spins when you flush the toilet). The deep-sea is then effected by how dense/cold the water gets, so as it gets heavier it sinks and moves slower than surface currents, causing a downward cycle effect. I can only imagine the earth spinning faster would affect the ocean stuff the most. In class they used a turntable as an example of Coriolis (the effect of earth spinning), where no matter how fast it spun the only change would be how far the "current", an arrow draw on paper spinning on the turntable, would reach around.

text:
To answer the question about what would happen to gravity if the earth started spinning faster: absolutely nothing. What you get instead is centripetal force, but the earth would have to spin ridiculously fast for centripetal force to be a significant factor. Assuming this is the case, you would effectively weigh less and this effect would be greatest at the equator.
It would also result in everything being pulled towards the equator slightly, which would mean catastrophic flooding as all the water flows towards what is now effectively lower ground.

text: As a 3D cgi artist, some things DO NOT need to be 3D animated. Stop motion and 2D animation are wonderful art forms and have charm that canâ€™t compare. Sadly, Princess and the Frog did not perform well in theaters, basically showing Disney that 2D animation doesnâ€™t bring in the big box office bucks like they used to. One issue for me, is that a lot of the 3D cgi movies all almost feel or look the same. They donâ€™t have a unique style to them, they all kinda blend together. The first PokÃ©mon movie is being remade as 3D cgi.... and it just lost something along the way in the transition to 3D. The style and feeling is just so generic now, when before you could easily pick out a scene from that movie and know it was the first movie. Thereâ€™s a lot of factors to why a project decides to go 3D, but I wish the overall feeling and style of the movie would be a factor. Though art goes through movements, so I hope weâ€™ll see a resurgence of 2D and stop motion, and as for myself and my career, a more stylish and unique execution of 3D.

text:
Fun-facts about the Disney 2D animation discussion at the beginning. The Princess and the Frog is not the last theatrical 2d animated Disney movie, Winnie the Pooh (2011) is. 

Princess and the frog despite being a box office hit, did not make the numbers Disney wanted. executives blamed 2 things: The release of James Cameron's Avatar a week later and the name of the film. Apparently they think the tittle gave off a "little girls only" vibe, and its the reason future princess Disney movies are titled the way they are. Winnie the pooh did bomb though, because it released the same weekend as Harry Potter the deadly hollows part 2.

all in all Princess had a budget of $105 Million and grossed $269 Million, while Winnie had a budget of $30 Million and grossed $50 Million. keep in mind this number does not include marketing cost.
